Reduce NJ temp data

head(NJ_temp) #first5rows - ,10 to increase rows
#fix date
NJ_temp$Date <- ymd(NJ_temp$Date) #replacementsamename

#reduce to columns we actually need
NJ_temp.r <- NJ_temp %>%
  select(Date, SuTemp)

#also, add region column
NJ_temp.r$region <- "NJ"

Reduce NC temp data

head(NC_temp)

#fix date
NC_temp$Date <- ymd(NC_temp$date)

#I notice that we have many measurements for a single day, let's take the average for each day
NC_temp.r <- NC_temp %>% #take NC_temp data frame and then...
  group_by(Date) %>% #group by Date of measurement
  summarise(SST = mean(WTMP_avg)) #take the average value for each Date and put into column SST (sea surface temperature)

#also, add new region column
NC_temp.r$region <- "NC"
NC_popcatchid$Date <- mdy(NC_popcatchid$Date)
NJ_popcatchid$Date <- ymd(NJ_popcatchid$Date)

Finally, we need to merge the NJ data table with the NC datatable

Fisher and Hogan 2007 Highlight some important ratios, so well calculate those as well. Specifically, we want to look at Overall, we found that a predictive model incorporating total length (TL), the square of caudal peduncle depth factor (CPDF2) and aspect ratio (AR) can be used to accurately predict swimming performance of a wide range of fish families

Morphometric ratios - Muscle ratio (MR) MA/BA - Propulsive ratio (PR) PA/BA - Fineness ratio (FR) TL/[(BW+BD)/2] - Aspect ratio (AR) (CFD/CFA) ^(1/2) - Caudal peduncle depth factor (CPDF) CPD/BD** note, was this measured correctly?
